<br>
Let me enlighten you on a few ways on how to get others to roleplay.  First, if you have a server that is dedicated to roleplaying, then you enforce it.  Simple enough.  If you are not sure how, then there are such measures as to TEACH other players what roleplaying is all about, give them a warning, or have the community reprimand or belittle those who don't.<br>
<br>
I would say that most on here remember Necanta, and one of Necanta's favorite ways of getting back at lazy, unimaginative players that detract from the game is to belittle them in front of everyone.  Or she would not group with them.  Or make the offenders feel ostricized from the community.  Then those people have a choice.  Either to join the other roleplayers, or to leave the server.  Before Necanta and Qaydin had crossed paths on TZ, Qaydin was not much into roleplaying.  But after I believe one encounter, all of that changed, and Qaydin became quite caught up in the concept and I was proud to find him not only a nasty opponent, but a very enjoyable one as well because of the way how he roleplayed. <br>
<br>
I have played roleplaying games for 20+ years now, be it table top, MMORPGs, or live roleplaying where the participants, be they players or &quot;monsters&quot; (non-players), dress up in costumes and ACT out their various roles.  Yes, it takes a bit of effort to try to &quot;get into character&quot;, but that extra bit of work just makes the entire experience THAT much more enjoyable for everyone.  These games are meant to be a distraction from real life events, like a movie, and allow ourselves to be involved in a fictious world where we can help perpetuate the experience with our fellow players.<br>
<br>
I could go on, but I have a feeling that this will all fall on deaf ears, which I feel would be unfortunate.  Funny how everyone forgets the &quot;RP&quot; in MMORPG.  But hells bells, at least my friends and I can pick and choose whom to play with in NWN.<br>
<br>
